  1. In this question well explore basic calculations with the Normal distribution, and investigate the Normality of the data set.

    1. Calculate the mean and standard deviation of all runners times. Store them in variables called xbarT and sT, and print them in the output.
    2. Suppose runners times were in truth Normally distributed with parameters \(\bar x\) and \(s\) from part a. Standardize the data (i.e., find z-scores) and create an appropriate plot to check for Normality.
    3. Repeate steps a.-b. for the females and males separately.
    4. What do the Q-Q plots tell us about our ability to do inference on this data set?
#Answer Number 4 here
xbarT = mean(runner_data$Time.Seconds)
sT = sd(runner_data$Time.Seconds)
xbarT
## [1] 15801.2
sT
## [1] 2470.742
runner_data_standardized = numeric(length(runner_data$Time.Seconds))

for (i in 1:length(runner_data$Time.Seconds)) {
  runner_data_standardized[i] = (runner_data$Time.Seconds[i] - xbarT) / sT
}

qqnorm(runner_data_standardized, main="z-scores from all runners")

#Assuming female is 1, male is 2
female_runners = runner_data[runner_data$Gender == 1,]
male_runners = runner_data[runner_data$Gender == 2,]

female_xbarT = mean(female_runners$Time.Seconds)
female_sT = sd(female_runners$Time.Seconds)
female_xbarT
## [1] 16477.64
female_sT
## [1] 2247.552
female_runner_data_standardized = numeric(length(female_runners$Time.Seconds))

for (i in 1:length(female_runners$Time.Seconds)) {
  female_runner_data_standardized[i] = (female_runners$Time.Seconds[i] - female_xbarT) / female_sT
}

qqnorm(female_runner_data_standardized, main="z-scores from all female runners")

male_xbarT = mean(male_runners$Time.Seconds)
male_sT = sd(male_runners$Time.Seconds)
male_xbarT
## [1] 15314.37
male_sT
## [1] 2509.931
male_runner_data_standardized = numeric(length(male_runners$Time.Seconds))

for (i in 1:length(male_runners$Time.Seconds)) {
  male_runner_data_standardized[i] = (male_runners$Time.Seconds[i] - male_xbarT) / male_sT
}

qqnorm(male_runner_data_standardized, main="z-scores from all male runners")

#These plots tell us the data is relatively normal

  1. We conclude the assignment with some standard analyses on the data set as a whole.

    1. Compute the 95% confidence interval for the mean race time of females. In a comment box, write the explicit interpretation of this confidence interval.
    2. Can we reject the null hypothesis that \(\mu_F = 16,500\) seconds at significance level \(\alpha = 0.05\)? Explain how you can know the answer without actually calculating the test statistic Hint: it has to do with your answer to part (a).
    3. Letting \(\mu_F\) be the mean race time for females and \(\mu_M\) the mean race time for males, compute the p-value for the hypotheses: \[ H_0:\mu_F = \mu_M \;\;\text{vs.}\;\; H_a:\mu_F\ne\mu_M \] Assume that \(\sigma_F\) and \(\sigma_M\) are unknown and may differ. Print the p-value under its calculation.
    4. Compute the 99% confidence interval for \(\mu_F - \mu_M\). To calculate your degrees of freedom, use the smaller of the two sample sizes. Print the confidence interval after its calculation.
    5. In a comment box, write a few sentences interpreting the results of your data analyses in this problem.
error = qnorm(0.975)*female_sT/sqrt(length(female_runners$Time.Seconds))
left = female_xbarT - error
right = female_xbarT + error
left
## [1] 16341.38
right
## [1] 16613.91
# b) Yes, 16,500 lies within the 95% confidence interval I calculated

t.test(female_runners$Time.Seconds, male_runners$Time.Seconds, conf.level=0.99)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  female_runners$Time.Seconds and male_runners$Time.Seconds
## t = 12.146, df = 2379.7, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 99 percent confidence interval:
##   916.3813 1410.1717
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  16477.64  15314.37



We can see that the sample mean of the female runners lies within the 95% confidence interval. As for the difference in means, we are able to reject the null hypothesis as the p-value is less than the significance level.

ANOVA

In the next problem, we are going to use Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) to reach the same conclusion that was reached in Number 5 regarding the difference of means between males and females.

  1. First do head(runner_data) to remind yourself of the variable names.
  2. Then make side-by-side boxplots of run times for men and women. The general form for this is boxplot(response ~factor, data=data_name) where response is the variable we are plotting (run times in seconds in our case) and factor is the categorical variable that separates the data into groups whose means we are comparing. Finally data_name is our data set. be sure you are using runner_data with the outliers removed.
  3. Be fancy and go back and put labels on the two boxplots in Part (b). You can use ?boxplot in the console to see how. You many find the vector c("men","women") useful.
  4. The Analysis of variance command works somewhat similarly. The general form is aov(response ~factor, data=data_name). Assign this command to the variable ANOVA and type ANOVA to see the two sources of variability and respective degrees of freedom.
  5. Which number describes Between Group variability and which describes Within Group Variability. (Use a comment box below.) You may notice that the aov command output uses the terms Model and Residuals. This is because the origin of the command is in Linear Regression, our next topic.
  6. To see the F-statistic and F-test results, you will have to use summary(ANOVA). In your answer box below, state the F-statistic and its p-value.
  7. Are we able to conclude that the average marathon run times of men and women are different? Explain.
  8. What is the lowest level of significance at which we could conclude men and women have different avarage marathon run times?
